nings":["English: status name for a steward or official, from Middle English <i>bailli</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>baillis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>, an adjectival derivative of <i>baiulus</i> ‘attendant, carrier, porter’).","English: habitational name from Bailey in Little Mitton, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>beg</i> ‘berry’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, from Middle English (Old French) <i>bailli</i> ‘outer courtyard of a castle’ (Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’, a derivative of <i>bailer</i> ‘to enclose’). This term became a placename in its own right, denoting a district beside a fortification or wall, as in the case of the Old Bailey in London, which formed part of the early medieval outer wall of the city."],"variants":[{"name":"Bailly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Emile, Marcel, Philippe.","French: occupational name for a steward or official, from Old French <i>baillif</i>. Compare   Bailey   4.","French: habitational name from (Le) Bailly, the name of several places in the northern part of France."]},{"name":"Bale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baile</i>, from Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’ (see   Bailey   3).","Breton (<b>Balé</b>): variant of   Balay  .","French: unexplained."]},{"name":"Baily","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayly","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Balay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Rajesh, Satish.","Altered form of English   Bailey  .","French: habitational name from any of various minor places so named."]},{"name":"Baile","meanings":["Spanish: status name for a steward or official, from Old Spanish <i>baile</i>, Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>; cognate with English   Bailey  .","French (southern): variant of   Bail  .","English: variant of   Bale  ."]},{"name":"Baillie","meanings":["Scottish:","from Older Scots <i>baillie</i>, <i>baili</i>. In Scotland, a baillie was a status name for any of various officials, including the chief magistrate in a barony and (later) the chief magistrate or administrative officer of a barony or district. Etymologically, this is the same word as English   Bailey  , but the functions as well as the spelling of the two officials were different in England and Scotland.","topographic name from Older Scots <i>bailli</i> ‘outer court of a castle’; see   Bailey   3 and   Bale   1."]},{"name":"Baley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Bailey was born in 1420, in Brockton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Matiolda Matilda Hamerton. He died after 1465, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1420–Aft 1465":"1420–pärast 1465","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1445–1489":"1445–1489","1420–1465":"1420–1465","1425":"1425","1489":"1489","1445":"1445","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","Aft 1465":"pärast 1465","about 1445":"umbes 1445","Brockton, Shropshire, England":"Brockton, Shropshire, England","Brockton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom